President Donald J. Trump has announced his intent to nominate Roderick C. Young of Virginia as a Judge on the United States District Court for the Eastern District of Virginia. Young currently serves as a United States Magistrate Judge on the same court and has previously held positions as an Assistant United States Attorney, Special Assistant United States Attorney, and Assistant Public Defender. He is also an Adjunct Professor at William & Mary Law School.

Additionally, Liam P. Hardy of Virginia has been nominated to serve as a Judge on the United States Court of Appeals for the Armed Forces. Hardy is currently a Deputy Assistant Attorney General for the Office of Legal Counsel at the United States Department of Justice. He has also worked as a litigation partner at Kirkland & Ellis, LLP and serves as a Lecturer on Law at Harvard Law School and an Adjunct Professor at Notre Dame Law School. Hardy has clerked for several judges, including Judge Margaret Ryan on the United States Court of Appeals for the Armed Forces, Chief Judge David B. Sentelle on the United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia, and Associate Justice Clarence Thomas on the Supreme Court of the United States.